         <t:listPerson>
            <t:person sex="1">
           
                  <t:persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth">ገብረ፡ መስቀል፡</t:persName>
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Gabra Masqal</t:persName>
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n2" type="alt">ኅሩይ፡ ወልደ፡ ሥላሴ፡</t:persName>
               <t:persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n2" type="normalized">Ḫǝruy Walda Śǝllāse</t:persName>
               <t:persName>
                  <t:roleName type="title">blātten getā</t:roleName>
               </t:persName>
                  
                  
                  
                  
                  <t:nationality type="Ethiopia"/>
                  <t:faith type="EOTC"/>
                  
                  
                 
                  <t:occupation type="political"> civil servant</t:occupation>
               <t:occupation type="literary">writer</t:occupation>
              
               <t:birth when="1878">He was born at <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4578Marhab">Marḥābete</t:placeName> 
                     in <t:date>1878</t:date>. </t:birth>
                  
                  
               <t:floruit notBefore="1914" notAfter="1938">He was a prominent politician and a
                  leading intellectual of the <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5226haylase">Ḫāyla Śǝllāse I</t:persName> I era. 
                  His personality was shaped by both traditional and modern education. 
                  He received a traditional education in the areas of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4544Manz">Manz</t:placeName> 
                  and <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5482Salale">Sälale</t:placeName>. 
                  Then, he joined the famous school of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2981Entott">Ǝnṭoṭṭo Raguʾel</t:placeName>
                  where he met his mentor and teacher <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9897WaldaGi">Wäldä Giyorgis</t:persName> who gave
                  him the name Ḫǝruy by which he has come to be known in history.    
               
                  Later Ḫǝruy acquainted with foreign ideas and languages. 
                  He learned English at Swedish mission school in northern outskirts of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1216AddisA">ʾAddis ʾAbabā</t:placeName>.
                  He was also able to acquire some French through association with a French veterinary team. 
                  He was also frequently travelling abroad. He served as a secretary of  
                  <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1216AddisA">ʾAddis ʾAbabā</t:placeName> municipality from <t:date>1914-15</t:date>, 
                  as acting mayor of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1216AddisA">ʾAddis ʾAbabā</t:placeName> from 1919-1921, 
                  as chief judge of special court from<t:date>1922-1926</t:date>, as a director-general of foreign minister from<t:date>1927-30</t:date> and finally as a 
                  foreign minister from <t:date>1931-36</t:date>.
                  Ḫǝruy  has left  his mark on national life, not only as a diligent civil servant but also as a prolific writer. 
                  He has to his name over 20 books and booklets. 
                  
               </t:floruit>
               <t:death when="1938">He died in exile at <t:placeName ref="https://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q21"> England </t:placeName> in <t:date>1938</t:date>.</t:death>
                  
                  
               </t:person>
               
               
         </t:listPerson>
         
         
